ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/image-8.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260622T092424Z
DESCRIPTION:Join Bangalore-based\, self-taught artist Nirupa Rao for a botanical sketching workshop inspired by her artistic practice and unique approach to observing and representing the natural world. Through guided exercises\, participants will learn how sketching plants in black and white can provide a strong foundation for botanical illustration\, helping develop an understanding of structure\, volume\, form\, and shading.\n\nThis introductory workshop is open to beginners as well as those with prior experience. Participants who have been practicing are welcome to bring colour media of their choice to further explore their work.\n\nThis workshop is presented in conjunction with the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260704T073000Z
DTSTART:20260704T060000Z
SUMMARY:The Art of Botanical Illustration
UID:1314@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/the-art-of-botanical-illustration/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/image-5.png
CATEGORIES:Online Talk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260618T095004Z
DESCRIPTION:Lover's Tryst\; Rajasthan\, India\; 1750–1800\; Gum tempera and gold on paper\; 30.7 x 23 cm. Courtesy The Cleveland Museum of Art: Mr and Mrs William H Marlatt Fund\nWhat might taste\, touch\, scent\, sound\, and emotion reveal about the history of art?\n\nBringing together artists\, critics\, historians\, and practitioners\, this three-part series explores how sensory approaches can expand our understanding of South Asia’s art and cultural histories — through subjects ranging from court paintings and garden cultures to kitchens\, workshops\, and cities.\n\nPresented in collaboration with IMPART\, this series is held in conjunction with the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire\, on view at MAP until 5 July 2026.\n\nScroll down to view the schedule\, learn more about the speakers.\n\n[DIALOGUE 1]\n\nWays of Feelings — An Introduction to Sensory History\n24 June | Wednesday | 7 PM (IST)\n\nDr Fatima Quraishi\, Dr Preeti Bahadur Ramaswami\, Vinit Vyas\n\nDrawing on court miniatures from the Himalayas to the Deccan\, this session provides a general introduction to sensory approaches in art history. It considers what these works reveal about people\, places\, cultures\, and lived experiences across time\; what it means to feel an image rather than merely see it\; and how such an approach might open up new ways of imagining the past.\n\n[DIALOGUE 2]\n\nSensoria Indica — On Scents\, Sounds and Gardens\n25 June | Thursday | 7 PM (IST)\n\nBharti Lalwani\, Indu Antony\, Dr Murad Khan Mumtaz\, Dr Nicolas Roth\n\nMoving through fragrance and botany\, music and materiality\, scents and the city\, this discussion looks closely at how non-visual senses were woven into early modern Hindustani paintings and how they continue to influence contemporary art techniques.\n\n[DIALOGUE 3]\n\nMaking Sense — On Tastes\, Touch and Labour\n26 June | Friday | 7:00 PM IST\n\nDr Arun Kumar\, Mallory Cerkleski\, Dr Neha Vermani\n\nExamining early-modern Mughal kitchens\, colonial artisanal workshops in north India\, and toddy shops in contemporary Kerala\, this conversation foregrounds the labour behind these practices. Drawing on a wide range of archival\, visual\, and oral sources\, it studies the politics of touch\, taste\, and taste-making in the South Asian context.
DTEND:20260626T150000Z
DTSTART:20260624T133000Z
SUMMARY:Garden of the Senses  — A Sensory History of Indian Art
UID:1311@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/garden-of-the-senses-a-sensory-history-of-indian-art/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/MAC.00468.jpg
CATEGORIES:Drop-in Sessions,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260623T050603Z
DESCRIPTION:Start with a dot\, build with shapes\, and bring it to life with colour. Inspired by Raza’s iconic geometric compositions\, explore how simple circles\, squares\, triangles\, and lines can come together to create powerful artworks that represent the universe through geometric forms and create an artwork that is uniquely your own.\n\nMake @ MAP is a series that allows you to explore our collection in an engaging and hands-on manner. These sessions allow you to create and take home a special souvenir of your visit. It is perfect for all ages — so bring your friends and family and get ready to make some art! No experience is necessary\, just a willingness to have fun and experiment with new materials.
DTEND:20260628T100000Z
DTSTART:20260628T060000Z
SUMMARY:Make @ MAP
UID:1323@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/make-map-2/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/IMG_7526.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260622T120641Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Rohan Patankar\nJoin Luru and MAP for a morning between an exhibition and a walk through Cubbon Park.\n\nWe begin at the Museum of Art &amp\; Photography (MAP) with a walkthrough of Beneath the Turning Sky\, followed by a guided walk through Cubbon Park with Joshua Muyiwa.\n\nInspired by Park Days\, Joshua's essay in Luru Issue 04: Nature_Nurture\, which recounts the oral history of Cubbon Park\, this guided walk invites participants to explore the histories\, memories\, and everyday encounters that shape one of Bengaluru's most beloved public spaces. Through stories\, observation\, and the perspectives of our fellow wanderers\, we'll discover the park in new ways. 
DTEND:20260627T060000Z
DTSTART:20260627T040000Z
SUMMARY:Luru x MAP: A Walk at Cubbon Park
UID:1319@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/luru-x-map-a-walk-at-cubbon-park/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/MV5BMWQ3ZDBmODQtMGIzOC00MTg2LWEwOTctODM4MmU0MDM5NGYyXkEyXkFqcGc@._V1_.jpg
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260625T073535Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: A still from Harikatha Prasanga (2016)\nJoin Ananya Kasaravalli as she takes us through her journey as a theatre artist\, actor and director and the fluidity with which her works move between mediums. In conversation with Sandhya Rani\, playwright and critic of theatre and cinema\, Ananya reflects on the shift in her practice from acting to filmmaking\, and on how her upbringing in a family deeply rooted in Kannada theatre and cinema shaped her lens. From her performances in films like Kaada Beladingalu (Jungle Moonlight) and Naayi Neralu (Shadow of the Dog)\, to her directorial debut Harikatha Prasanga (Chronicles of Hari) her body of work explores gender and identity—inviting us to look at how cinema reflects and shapes society.\n\nThe event is presented as part of a monthly series that brings in artists and artistic practices rooted in Bengaluru\, developed in collaboration with Ananya Drishya.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n&nbsp\;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n
DTEND:20260703T133000Z
DTSTART:20260703T123000Z
SUMMARY:Growing with and through Films
